The paper discusses the problem of open-ended evolution in biological and technological systems, which involves understanding the mechanisms for ongoing growth of complexity. This topic is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including neural networks (cs.NE), dynamical systems (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), control systems (cs.SY), and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper specifically uses dynamical systems theory to uncover mechanisms for open-ended evolution, suggesting that cs.DS is the most likely sub-category. However, the paper also discusses cellular automata and state-dependent dynamics, which are relevant to other sub-categories such as cs.NE, cs.AI, cs.SY, and cs.LG.
